segments.text: Now, you were working in an advertising firm when the Depression begins, is that correct?
And your work doesn't ever suffer during the Depression?
Oh yes, it suffered.
The main thing, we didn't have a preponderance of weight.
And our council was very small.
It was Anderson and Clayton.
We had a house, all of them, and some advertising.
But we had what's called a subsidiary of Anderson and Clayton, like Southern Baggin and other places.
But we just had nothing to do with it.
It was a leisure place.
And by the same, that didn't help me to get along with my finance.
We had time weekends at night.
But I kept on essentially pencil work because that was a medium that I had found myself in.
And I had Chip.
I had brought that in a while ago while I was in New York.
And I got this story in the magazine, Eberhard Faber Pencil Company, old Brooklyn.
They got in touch with me, sent somebody over to look and talk to me.
And they talked me to come over and work with them on testing out different pencils.
And they got a beautiful brochure around New York of my pencil work with National.
But that's when I got, say, absorbed with pencil work.
And it's a tremendous medium.
You don't think it isn't because they use it.
It's fascinating, but it offers so much, and people don't realize the hardness of the pencil.
I've tried everything.
It goes from a 7-H onto a 6-B.
That's about 10 pencils, but barefoot edges.
But I've experimented.
I learned to feel on different papers, and I've made it.
It was such a tremendous, absorbing thing.
But that's why we do so much pencil work.
I've got it done.
In a sense, only pencil work.
And at the moment, I'm going back to it again.
But, of course, it's a forgotten medium.
I might say not forgotten, but it's an ignored one.
And it takes a lot of basic, well, sometimes when I get up there, I can show you just what I mean, why you can use the procedure with pencil.
But I stay with every hard favor, or just off and on, but I got advertisements out for them, and brochures.
And it was good to use in architectural work and everything.
But that's what artists nowadays do not get into that realm of things, that basic drawing, I might call it, with pencil.
Pencil is a medium to use, because I try to use all of them now, but everything is available.
Every day there's something new that comes out, and I just say, well, let's give it a fling.
It's a challenge.
It's a constant challenge.
There's so much of it in art.
Of course, I'm devoting it to my subject,
But I went across the agency.
I did a tremendous lot of work for Humble, if you know what I mean.
See, that was one of the breaks I did get.
I called it the breakers.
I worked like Humble Company, Standard Oil.
I worked for them.
I was sent out into the field constantly and on expense account.
Yeah, but you were freelancing, though, when you were with Humble, were you not?
No.
I was with the agency, no.
I was a partner in the agency, but I was not on salaries.
I was free of that, but I didn't want it.
I wanted to be a free agent.
So I stayed with them and got, because my participation with the agency did what it wanted, but I stayed with the agency for contact.
No one wanted it that way, but I went out on my own, got everything piecemeal.
But then I picked up some others too, other accounts on my own.
Dow Chemical, I did a lot of work for them, independent of the agency.
But they wanted it because it didn't hurt them any to have the name clients.
I had some bigger accounts there.
This is in the 30s still?
No, that was way back.
I'm jumping the gun on you.
But I went through the usual routine.
Now, because you were with Humble Way and so forth in the 40s and 50s.
Well, yes, I was there, but we got Humble accounts in, I think, 1934 when we picked it up.
It started with the house organs at that time, the lubricator and the beads.
And the Humble Way, which came later on into the 40s, we got instigated to Humble Way.
And that's when I got the Texas sketchbook and everything.
Because they sent me on the road.
They wanted to get...
this particular phase of it, I don't know if it's the texana in it, but the romantic side of it.
I had a friend, Tank Fields, was my partner in this type of thing, but we traveled, researched, but that was a beautiful assignment, a Texas sketchbook.
Then we did The Prince, I don't know, just, well, having this sort of, some amazing answer, but it might be two or three hundred for The Prince, something like that.
But I was constantly,
Right with my fine art, to some extent.
You make competitions.
I'm not advertising what these are, pictures.
All that's fine art.
And they made, of course it was a beautiful relation job.
I say for humble, it was good for me, but I got recognition.
I mean, sacred image.
Believe me, you need one.
All the talent in the world don't help if you don't have content.
I was so fortunate in that respect that I had my association with business, the business world,
And on end of it, there's some wonderful patrons, but I've had a much better break than so many artists have had, because not any outstanding talent, but I had the connections.
Believe me, they count.
I'm telling you, but I've seen some beautiful talent that never could get on to first base because they didn't have anyone.
You have to have a good dealer if he's for you, he can help you, but a good dealer, but it's a hard road.
God, you're sick of it.
So many of them, they're turning out now, but some of them are magnificent artists.
But you're striving for recognition, you just have to be patient.
But I just put myself up, it's not a, it's getting things, it's a hard way, I might call it that, but it was tremendously worth it, God, yes.
Now, while you were working with the, you stayed with the advertising agency all during the 30s then?
Yeah, oh yeah, 30s and 40s and 50s, and then the early 60s.
I had two partners went to war, at reserve offices when the war was, 42 or 43.
But they went and left the agency on my hands.
I was overnight, guess what?
Buck, it's yours.
We had a meeting with the directors, stockholders, had some humble people in the agency, had stock in it, and so did Anderson Clayton.
They want to close it up.
They had a meeting, said, Buck, this is it.
We said, oh, sorry, but there's no one to carry us.
They said, whoa, you're going to give me a chance.
Don't you do this to me.
We're going to keep this thing going.
And if it doesn't prove hard, I'll step aside very quickly, easily.
And so we did, and they said, all right, well, give me a vote of confidence, God bless you, you know.
Now all of a sudden, overnight, I have, I'm with the second biggest agency in the state, and I had a thing of the administrator.
I said, well, now, oh, I ran scared, God, for Watkinson.
Whoa, that's a little praying hole in me.
So, well, I won't go into all the detail, but they had a lot of dead wood in there.
I got rid of all the dead wood, and the agency says, this is a house kicking.
Then I brought in key people, even Atlanta, the West Coast,
and put them in there and allocate it the right way, and have them all the same way.
But I learned another thing in the administration.
The best of my ability, but I mean, top of everything, get confidence in your personnel, which I did, your participation, and everything, but it was beautiful.
And they came back, they couldn't believe it.
We got the cars held up, didn't get in the red.
So I turned over to his agency, that would have gone four years, I think.
Thank you.
Oh, he had another time over, but he was,
I had a problem, you know.
I got booted out of the Army.
I had the finest career anybody could have ever wanted, right at the top of the range, but he couldn't contain himself.
But anyhow.
Was it an alcohol problem?
Oh yeah.
They all had them, some of them, my own.
No, it's a nemesis.
I've had it all along, but I've had to find answers to that too.
But it got into this terrible environment.
Oh my God, 20 hours a day, but this gold, please.
So, no, that's why I didn't want to have to find answers for that and start a whole new career.
But it's terrible how much of it is transpired in advertising agencies.
I don't have the clients to entertain them all the time.
No.
But... Well, when did you find your place at Quirrell?
About a year ago.
About a year ago.
Well, before that, though, you were...
I was here.
Yeah, but you... Oh, I know that.
But, I mean, before you came here, though, you were out in the hill country for a while.
Oh, yes, I was there.
We had our place, a beautiful place in the hill country.
Uh-huh.
And we were out there, and that was terrible.
That was the worst thing that ever happened to me because when they got back and watched Joe and Paul come,
Thank you.
They said, thank God.
Now you need to rest, Buck.
Thank you.
Oh, what a beautiful cloud of glass.
Yeah, goody, goody, goody.
So what?
And I said, what you want you to do is go back to your place and hunt and relax and retire.
Well, I went up there in the dead of winter.
It was desolate.
We didn't have any summer homes or anything like that.
And that was a horrible experience.
That's when I really got no pride, no problems.
Yeah.
Now, let's say that you go to hunt when, Buck?
When do you go to hunt then?
Oh, I just, I don't hardly go to all of them.
No, I mean, when did you go to hunt?
We bought the, no, because we bought this hunt place back in 19, it was in 34 when we bought the hunt place.
Okay.
And we just kept it as a summer place.
It had those houses on it.
And finally, I went to hunt more or less after I got back from the war.
They got back and went up there to try to carry on with my work, paint and just go ahead.
But I couldn't attack myself.
There was tremendous letdown.
Mm-hmm.
And that ain't a forlorn, there's nothing like a communication.
Here I was with artists, businessmen, all of a sudden, why would, with your people out there, they're beautiful people, and what they say, well, what be you doing this morning, things like that.
I didn't have any, no communication.
And somebody just come and say, gee, I like what you're doing, I like this new book, but never.
But you need that.
Not to go ahead and build up your vanity or your,
self-confident, but I just need it down there.
Just get a kind word.
It's better than all the monetary remuneration you can get.
I'd say, I think in my mind, I like, don't want to praise, but I do like a few kind words.
Yeah, and don't you want to talk to people about your work?
Oh, yes.
My God, yes.
Oh.
It would seem to me like the New York experience would have been, for example, for you to broaden yourself in the sense of talking to people who were doing other things.
Oh, yes, that's right.
But in my, in talking in my vernacular, my God, yes, that was the beauty of that New York.
And I worked with these, the top people there, I mean, Hodders, Pentland, they were, they were top performers.
And I worked, I served apprenticeship on them.
The Hugh Ferris is a marvelous one.
And, uh,
I went up to see him, showed him my work, and said, gee, I'd like to use you part-time.
He said, you want to come up?
And so between four and five, or four to six and a half, I'd go to work with him.
Or Precious, just pick up.
Then I'd go to others.
I learned pencils through Otto Eggers, another one, and Chester Price with Wolfman.
But I went to, and they took me in so beautifully.
Because I wanted to learn.
I said, you've got potential.
And they, because that's where I said, another big advantage I had.
But I would like to work with a top performer.
Well, you can get a lot of it to hurt you, but it's like teaching art.
They can destroy it.
Art teachers can destroy you very fast.
I've seen some.
Anyhow, but I said I had a beautiful advantage.
But everything, you know, I look at it, and I seem to fall into place all the time.
I get dead desperate at times.
God, God, I'm mad at you.
I was doing this A&M series here when I stayed there two years.
There was a booger.
Because there was something important.
It was wonderful to do it.

It wasn't always highly inspirational, the architecture wasn't, and all those things, but I had to try to do the best I could with it, namely just putting kids in there, and bicycles and things like that, and honorizing.

But I spent two years, you know, that thing, but I enjoyed that because I did, I've done innumerable sketches the first year that I haven't shown anybody yet, but the preliminaries, I'd ride, they'd call it, they'd ride bicycles, and then, and building a bonfire.
I spent a week out there watching them when they pulled those,
The log was up by hand, and I got a whole series on that.
In fact, I hadn't even seen it.
I was talking to somebody about, yes, they're buckwires, and she said, my God, Wayne, why can't we use those somewhere down the line to show how you arrived at these things?
But I hadn't given it a thought.
But that was a really rugged one.
But I stayed up here.
Of course, I liked associating with Frank.
Being here was, we always meet what you call top performers, whatever people, good writers.
nationally known people.
Now this next week Alfred Knopf's coming down.
He's one of the great book men in America.
But he's going to be here for lunch and guests.
And all of these people are going to come.
But they're marvelous people.
They're big people.
And it's been a tremendous asset to me.
Because it gave me some of my self confidence.
Because they are so humble and beautiful.
But the bigger they are, I find out, the more delightful they are in understanding.
But I'm going back now tomorrow.
I'm trying to finish my wake up at Westhoff, where I'm on right now, for the third book.
And they want me to stay on here, but I don't want to right now.
But I got the Freedom up there, till you see it.
1100 acre range, I'm right in the middle of it.
It's old custodian, got all my beautiful cattle, and carpentry, and cattle, nature.
But it's a delight.
Then I come back here now, but this place has been held for me.
I went to see Jack Williams the other day, the whole afternoon with Jack and Margaret and told him about what I was doing and said, Buck, just do what you want to do.
This place will always be yours.
I said, I may want to come back sometime.
It's been a long tenure, I don't know.
I'm not going to make any plans no more.
Don't pin me down.
Don't fence me in.
But I mean, it won't work.
When they come back from the war then, Buck, in 1945, then you, then you go out to... To go to Hunt.
Then you go to Hunt for a while.
Yeah.
How long do you stay at Hunt?
Oh, I guess a couple of years.
It was a devastating, but it almost polished me off, I must say.
Then we came back to Houston.
They wanted me back at the agency.
They had, they said, got a new place.
So I joined, and then I went to find this place on Lubbock.
We had a marvelous old apartment.
I reconverted, and I started back here with the agency.
And had a nice go with it.
I was very happy.
I got back with what you call associations that I needed.
That's a load.
And you get to see good shows and even exhibits sometimes.
You had all these private galleries I could run around and I could see what my fellow artists were doing.
You have to have it.
Some artists don't, like you take Winslow Homer.
He was tremendously introverted.
I mean, he just almost despised this fellow man.
And he threw rocks at people.
I talked to some of the people who went up there.
The interviewer, he said, he and his gardeners got into trouble.
I mean, he even had a gun.
But he didn't.
But look what the way he accomplished that.
See?
You can go ahead and allocate your time to idle visitations and people who have nothing to contribute and beat you to death.
But you have to be very discretionary and discretionary in who you're associated with, too.
Now, you continued your own work, though, when you got back to Houston in 47, because you paid... Oh, I came here.
Yeah, you paid a whole lot between 47 and... Oh, yeah.
I think I got more than five knots there.
And, of course, Meredith Long took me on about eight years ago, I guess.
Now, when you come back and you rejoin the agency in 47, did you freelance, too, then, about it?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, I freelanced in 47.
I said I did work for Dark Chemical, one of the big towns.
I did them.
Not for them, not even for DuPont.
I went down to the coal mines in Peonia, but you're talking about something, in Colorado.
Got on in there with a man, he had a sketch just like this.
Couldn't use any, couldn't take pictures, but I want to get, I want to get, I'll show you all that, but people don't know that I worked for DuPont in the coal mines, which I did.
Well, I didn't realize you'd been with DuPont.
Now, I knew you'd been with that when you worked for Humboldt.
Yeah, but I just worked for DuPont, too.
But that was a booger.
Yeah.
I read about these people being trapped like that, so I felt all the time when the beam was going to come down.
Well, it was interesting.
And then when you, by the 50s you were working all the time with Humboldt, almost all together.
Humboldt took other assignments on.
We had the City National Bank, that big new bank building, but we had about 25 accounts.
And I did actually, when I had Coon Paint Company, I took a look at some, Dental Maze, Ms. Bear's Bread, Sanitary.
But I designed all the posters and the land, everything for those people.
I don't know how I did it now.
I couldn't.
But it was just, I don't know, but it just said, damn it, you got to do it.
But it was rough.
How large was the agency then?
Oh, well, I think at that time, we were about at least third in the state of Texas.
There was Tracy Lock Dawson.
You know, over here there's some Glenn Advertising Agency, and I served as a big top performer.
We had about, didn't have to do the whole size, but 25, more than that person there.
So when you would, when you did the layouts, would you do the whole layout yourself, or would you assign it to people?
Oh, I assigned, finally I got to where I got a coterie of artists that do special types of things, good layout artists, the ones that do

away from certain food products and all those figures, but no, and then we'd form stuff out to different, I had a lot of freelance artists start coming to Houston, we'd just form work out, but the layouts, but I did more finish work, I guess, in every category, except real, but I did a lot of figure work, people don't realize, illustration, too.
I did, but, no, my, it hadn't,
I haven't divulged too much of what I've done, actually, to people not aware of the work I've done in advertising.
I think I'll be now on the Times the humble way, in my two books, in the Texas, but that's as far as, I mean, advertising, I've got just as much of that, and of course I still have all that.
I'll bring it back and keep some of it, but I haven't tremendously done it.
By this time, you're talking about roughly the mid-50s someplace.
And you're on the road a great deal.
When did you decide to leave the agency?
I didn't leave the agency.
Well, it was about 66, I think.
66, yeah.
In fact, I got this retirement status at that time.
But I never did leave it.
They kept my office.
They said I didn't have to retire.
It was a reminder.
We were submerged by the McCann Air Force.
than the New York people, because they just changed the whole ballgame for us.
I mean, approaches like technical motivation, research, and all that type of thing.
But it worked.
But we had time trying to get adjusted to that.
But we sold out our stock, too.
I sold my mechanics every bit of it.
And when I left, of course, they told me that.
Well, thank you, blah, blah, blah.
God bless you and all that.
This office is yours as a memorial."
Hell, I wasn't going.
I said, whenever you're back, it'll be there.
Just open it up and go back.
In a week, I had all the Yankees, a couple of Yankees were in there already.
They called me up.
Nice people.
I said, well, that's the nature of the game.
I didn't care.
Did you go back to hunt then in the 60s?
I somehow have you placed there in the 60s, Bob.
I was there in the 60s.
Yeah, we went back and gave it another try after we got out.
Oh, we kept our Houston place.
We had a nice home in Houston on Auburn Street, West University.
Came back there now and then, but we just stayed and hunted periodically, I must say.
We kept it mainly in summer and spring and fall, but in winter it's just not good right now.
I'm tempted to go up there.
But I would go back now, and of course, we have a beautiful spot.
Oh my God.
One of the finest places on the river.
But I have 12 acres up there, and it's worth quite a sum of money.
So I don't know what to do with it, but anyhow.
But of course, the thing was, Ruth Lee was working up there too, and she was very strong with the UDC, the Daughters of the Confederacy.
She was a historian, but she, magnificent work she did for them, research and making plans.
But she's gone.
Dead hospital three years now, just down, down, down, just a vegetable.
But there's a woman, one of the most remarkable talents, being a women's talisman.
But she just, I could have happened to me.
I said, why in the world have you?
Well, the doctor said, but it's uncanny the way you survived, which had been true.
But right now, then I had, I was paralyzed in 74 completely.
The side went out.
I was laying in a wheelchair in a walking frame and finally everything came back.
Yeah, I remember that in 74.
Man, that's how you feel.
You lay out there.
I was 14, I was out there in the rocks.
I couldn't even move.
But it's one of those things, well, good, you know, it happened.
Maybe that's what you should have happened.
I don't talk, look very philosophical, acceptance.
Then I had this cancer operation, which was last year, July.
Found this thing started acting up on my leg.
Boy, I didn't pay attention to it.
I was just doctoring, you know.
It was Sharon Steen.
She was my business manager, the oldest person.
When she saw it, my God, I said, you're all really in trouble.
So I see this doctor, I don't go to that, Dr. High in Cuero, and he said, well, that's Anderson.
They ran a camera, whatever it is, and said, you're going straight to Anderson.
Which they did, and then he ripped me open, took me out, and put cotton seeds on or something, and took a lot of me.
But that's all.
I mean, it was another month.
It had been too late.
I'd been up here.
But I went through that, and I feel about as well as I've felt in my life now.
And I've been exercising for a long while, but I just feel like I'm leaving.
When did you decide to come back to A&M?
In 72?
I was 72.
It was later than that.
I came to A&M, S.C.
I must have been 74.
I came up here.
I had a paralysis.
I had to come out.
I came up after that.
This thing here, I was fortunate.
I was here before Frank came in.
I was here before since, yeah, 72.
Oh, yeah.
But I went on back to hunt.
But I was here by myself until Frank, they moved, saw this wonderful Bailey here, came in.
It was what they wanted.
So the press came.
And then Frank wanted me to join up.
They said, we want you to be part of this thing.
I said, I'll go along with you.
I was a kid, so I've had a nice build up.
They've been beautiful people to be around.
But Frank,
My association with him has been tremendously rewarding at Rosemary's of mine, but I don't know, everything I have, of course, I've had rosebud, but it's been as a beautiful pattern for me.
I always look at something, what is this thing?
I've learned to accept it, but sometimes it bewilders me, it really does.
Why?
Why am I still around?
See?
But I'm functioned by Elizabeth.
So maybe there's a purpose.
But of course, the Steens were beautiful to me.
I went down there for the Turkey Festival.
They had bought our place, our charity, over here.
Our old house, and they had, oh, God, they did a magnificent job of refurbishing their wealthy people.
And they had this big ranch in the west over there, 100 acres.
So I just went out there and spent a week in that big ranch house.
I said, I don't want to go back there.
There's a freedom.
And I stayed on and on.
I called back and said, when are you coming in?
He said, in a week.
I said, I don't know.
Jack said, Buck, you're a resident.
I said, you ought to come back now and just raise it.
I said, Jack, I'm going to give it every consideration.
He's laughing.
No, but I will.
But I want to retain this.
I don't know what's in store.
Maybe I'll be back.
But it's not, it's a little bit too confining for me.
This is just a little room in the boarding house.
I spread my wings.
Was there anybody close to you when you were a queer old?
Just out there by yourself?
Well, I'm not supposed to be.
I'm not supposed to drive a car by myself, but I do it all.
No, I said, when you say you can't do it, I said, well, hell, I can't.
I mean, it's a silly, as a childish attitude, but that's the way I feel.
No.
No, it's stubbornness that's supposed to be.
Buck, you've probably become now, in the last six or seven years, the best known of the Texas artists.
I guess so.
What's been your reaction to that?
Because as we've been talking, you know, certainly I suspect even in the 50s, you know, when I first began your stuff with Humble Way, you weren't really that well known as a fine artist.
No, until Meredith took me over, of course.
I've had some good luck, but he gave me what's called image.
He's a good man, but he gave me these two beautiful shows that started me out, because it came almost a sell-out.
He had one last October.
It went over good, and I've got a new deal in Dallas with Meredith, and they're going to take a damn view of it.
I'm not married to Meredith, but this Bill Baker, they've got a marvelous brand gallery in Dallas.
But he took me.
I took nine of my pieces out, they came to see me.
He said, oh, let me have them.
But I said, I'm not, but I am not obligated to marry.
But he said, we need, I need, I want to get into North Texas, too.
Why not just confine myself to the, to marry this little premise?
So, he's going to have this huge opening up there, March the 25th.
God, what a magnificent gal he's put in.
But he, he's got my things up there, and he's already sold quite a few.
He said,
But I'm not out to make a killing and all, I'm not, but I just wanted to perform, because it's nice to have a substantial income.
You bet.
You bet.
I did, because that's another thing in my favor.
But I've made lots of investments in stocks and things.
I've got a dividends company.
I've got a source of income outside of my own by investments.
It's a place I would hunt for, $80,000 or more.
I don't, it don't mean, I just want to be comfortable.
I said, I ought to go out now, boy, this kid come here, get me a Rolls Royce Silver Cloud, and look and say, hey, you peasants.
You know, but that's, but I got smaller, I don't care about that.
No, I should be a world traveler, but I don't kind of, of course, I wouldn't want to go out and kick up my heel, but she's hopeless.
You know, you got to do something, oh, that is really a terrifying experience.
Not terrifying, but sorry to go to state hospital.
And intense care wasn't sick.
